 aspects of the post-apartheid rhetoric of commemoration and national unity to their colonialist roots. This detailed and compelling volume contributes significantly to current trends in post-apartheid scholarship. Moran emphasizes the need for a cautious interrogation of the colonial archive and scrutiny of critical discourses used by the would-be postcolonial intellectual, and poses a timelychallenge to those committed to exorcising that legacy. Shane Moran teaches at the University of KwaZulu-Natal.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aApartheid. 0aLanguage and languagesxOrigin. 0aRacism in language. 0aSan (African people). 4aAfrican Studies. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / African.2bisacsh  aApartheid.  aBushmen.  aColonialism.  aColonialist roots.  aCultural racism.  aEdward Said.  aEthno-aesthetic figuration.  aIdeology.  aJacques Derrida.  aLanguage.  aMartin Bernal.  aPost-apartheid rhetoric.  aRacial discrimination.  aSouth Africa.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781580467315?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781580467315423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781580467315/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles